<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: MegaMan Savestate Patch: allows savestates on real Hardw]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11938&amp;p=135298#p135298"><![CDATA[
Yes, you could save a game pretty much like a savestate. CHR RAM is potentially a problem depending on how much you do with it (As the original post mentions). If your game is already using a large portion of the SRAM for its gamestate, that may also present a problem. (Being in SRAM already, it would be saved. But power could be cut between updates of things, so you'd probably want it stored again for the actual save.)<br /><br />I guess it'd be harder to implement, but it wouldn't be very much harder except for the cases above.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3504">Kasumi</a> — Mon Oct 20, 2014 6:25 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
